Can you also provide an explanation of what the `std::boolalpha` statement does in the C++ example usage code?﻿#Explanation of `std::boolalpha` in C++ example usage

`std::boolalpha` is a standard library flag provided by the C++ streaming library, which helps to control how booleans are printed. By default, boolean values (i.e., `true` and `false`) are printed as string literals "true" and "false" respectively, but `std::boolalpha` lets you control this behavior and print boolean values as `true` and `false`.

In the example usage code I provided for the `is_prime` function, we have used it along with `std::cout` to display the results of the function call. By default, `std::cout` prints `true` and `false` as string literals, which may make the results more difficult to understand. Using `std::boolalpha` before the `<<` operator sets the bool-alpha flag to true, which means that boolean values will be printed as `true` or `false`.

Here's an example to demonstrate the difference:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <ios>

bool is_prime(int number);

int main() {
    int number1 = 17;
    int number2 = 15;

    std::cout << "Is " << number1 << " prime? ";
    std::cout << is_prime(number1) << std::endl;

    std::cout << "Is " << number2 << " prime? ";
    std::cout << is_prime(number2) << std::endl;

    // Set boolean output to true (i.e., use `true`/`false` instead of string literals)
    std::cout << std::boolalpha
              << "Is " << number1 << " prime? " << is_prime(number1) << std::endl;
    std::cout << std::boolalpha
              << "Is " << number2 << " prime? " << is_prime(number2) << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Without `std::boolalpha`, the output will be:

```
Is 17 prime? 1
Is 15 prime? 0
```

With `std::boolalpha`, the output will be:

```
Is 17 prime? true
Is 15 prime? false
```

